node.contents: I have a JFormattedTextField where I want only alphanumeric characters to be inserted. I am trying to use this code to launch a JDialog when the user types a non-allowed character, and in case everything is ok to get the string from the JFormattedTextField. When I run this code, no JOptionPane will come up when I type a symbol. I am aware that there is something wrong with my code, but due to my little experience I cannot identify it. I would appreciate some help.

node.contents:
The other answers are hitting the problem right on, but I noticed one that is more of a logical error or a preference.
The problem is that it warns the user every time when it updates and contains a character. What I see happening is someone types/pastes in multiple symbols, and when they try to backspace/delete them one at a time, they are spammed with warning dialogs because there is still a symbol in it. The simplest way to fix this would be to create a method that acknowledges (but does not spawn a warning message for) the fact that there is a symbol inside whenever the removeUpdate method is called. Another possibility is to have it reject the input and spawn a warning message when the text box is "completed", i.e. if they finish filling out a form it may be in, or whatever situation you are using the text box.
Just a thought, it's more of a aesthetic thing than a practical change.
